<p style="text-align: justify;">The ruling means the issue must head back to where it stood four years ago, in front of the BLNR.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">"My clients and I are ready to move forward in a new process. It\'s going to take years to come to make its way through the different levels of litigation," said Richard Naiwi Wurdeman.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">Following the ruling, Wurdeman had a strong message for Governor David Ige.</p>
"He owes the people an apology for violating their civil liberties. He owes the Hawaiians an apology, the general community an apology, and I hope all those charges that are pending against the protectors will be dropped because really it was all based on false premises," said Wurdeman.
<p style="text-align: justify;">The following statement is from Henry Yang, Chair of the TMT International Observatory Board of Directors, regarding Wednesday\'s ruling:</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">"We thank the Hawaii Supreme Court for the timely ruling and we respect their decision. TMT will follow the process set forth by the state, as we always have. We are assessing our next steps on the way forward. We appreciate and thank the people of Hawaii and our supporters from these last eight-plus years."</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The next move would likely be a hearing in front of the BLNR.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">"Today\'s decision provides direction to a new Land Board and another opportunity for people to discuss Mauna Kea\'s future. The Attorney General\'s office will be advising the Land Board regarding next steps," said State Attorney General Douglas Chin.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">The University of Hawaii weighed in as well.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">"The University of Hawaii continues to believe that Mauna Kea is a precious resource where science and culture can synergistically coexist now and into the future, and remains strongly in support of the Thirty Meter Telescope. UH is currently reviewing the court\'s decision to determine the best path forward," said Dan Meisenzahl, a UH spokesperson.</p>
<p style="text-align: justify;">If TMT is to go forward with its project, it would have to go through the permitting process once again. Attorney Richard Wurdeman believes the Supreme Courts Decision could put construction on hold for several years. It\'s been on hold since April.</p>
